{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_kale_ver01/data/2017236974/00279558078/1945092001/0857.xml":{"full_text":"Unemployment Insurance\nFund Expected To Prove\nStrong Defense In County\n\u2019men wall tax (jounty entering re\nronversion, North Carolina un\nemployment insurance funds of\nover $105,000,000 is expected to pro\nve a strong defense against econo\nmic upset, both for the community\nand for those workers who may be\nlaid off.\nA survey just completed for the\nHerald by the Unemployment Com\npensation Commission reveals:\n(1/ That Unemployment insurance\n%>uld pour as much as $J03,000 back\ninto the county\u2019s stream of com\nmerce over a period of about four\nmonths. This flow, of course, would\nnot be kept up over any prolonged\nperiod.\n(2) That butchers, bakers, groc\ners, landlords, milk companies, and\nother purveyors of the necessities\nof life would find this income a\ngood initial cushion against a poss\nible depression period.\nA (3) That unem'Dlovment inauran\nce could make up about 5j% of\nthe wages loss that insured work\ners would suffer through plant\nshut-downs for brief periods. This\npercentage would decrease greatly\nwith prolonged unemployment.\nIn a series of two articles, of\nwhich this is the first, the working\nand effect of unemployment insur\nance are explained. On the basis of\nthese, workers in plants and the\n^.business people of the county may\n^know what to expect if lay-offs\nreach substantial proportions.\nUnder the North Carolina unem\nployment insurance law, weekly\ncash payments are made to jobless\nwho can under its protection and\nmost workers in business and ind\nustry are protected, provided they\nwork for firms employing eight or\nmore persons. Not protected by the\nUnemployment insurance law are\nagricultural and domestic work\ners, government employees, em\nployees of nonprofit organizations.\nUnemployment insurance pay\nments may run as long as 16 weeks\nand may amount to as much as $20\na week, provided the worker has\nearned enough \u201ccredits\u201d while he\nwas employed. The average benefit\namount is expected to be about $12\na week, nearly all insured work\ners will be eligible for the maximum\nduration of benefits provided by the\nNorth Carolina law.\nApproximately 6,794 workers in\nHalifax County hold jobs protected\nby unemployment insurance, accor\nding to figures of the Unemploy\nment Compensation Commission.\nTheir estimated yearly wages total\n$9,021,852, or about $176,899 a week.\nIf ten percent of them, or 679 work\ners, were laid off it would mean\nthat wages amounting to over\n$17,000 a week would stop. If 20 per\ncent were laid off, the wages loss\nwould come to more than $34,000\na week.\nThis wage loss would soon be re\nflected throughout the county\u2019s\nwhole economy and a small-size de\npression might get underway.\nU nemployment Compensation\npaymentsto jobless workers, how\never, will do much to counteract\nany downward trend. If 20 percent\nof the workers are layed off and\nare qualified for unemployment\nbenefits, their weekly payments\nmight total $18,844 or 564 persent\nof their weekly wages, and a subs\ntantial cushion for them and for\nthe community as well. If 40 per\ncent were laid off, unemployment\ninsurance would pour $37,688 a we\nek into the county trade channels\nthrough the workers\u2019 spending for\nthe necessities of life. Thus unem\nployment insurance could pour\nmore than $J03,000 back into the\ncounty\u2019s stream of business in\nabout four months.\nThe butcher, the grocer, theland\nlord, the baker, and all others who\nsupplyed the daily needs of life\nwould be the frist to feel any mark\ned decrease in the county\u2019s payroll\nand they would benefit most quick\nly from the unemployment insuran\npayment made to their customers.\nSinse the North Carolina law limits\nbenefits payments for total unem\nployment compensation stream\nwould diminish steadily if substan\ntial numbers remained unemployed\nover long periods.\nUnemployment insurance pay\nments would go only to eligible\nworkers who are willing and able\nto work, if jobs are available. They\nwould be required to register for\nwork every week, and accept refer\nrals jobs. Thus business and indus\ntry are assured of a ready labor\nsupply, as its plans for new work\ntake shape.\nDnrino\u2019 lin om nl mrrvi 4\nsurance payments in North Caro\nlina reached their lowest level. Only\n$325,047.00 was paid out in bene\nfits. The higest level was attend in\n1938, the frist year that unemploy\nment insurance went into effect in\nthis state,when $8,159,U3.00 was\npaid out. The following table shows\nthe tendssince them:\n1939 .$4,256,854.00\n1940 .j4,380,305.00\n1941 3,314,228.00\n1942 .(2,781,927.00\n1943 592,334.00\n1944 325,047.00\nPayments this year to June to\ntaled $139,119.00 In the readjust\nment period ahead, the figures are\nexpected to rise.\nHistory: Petain tried to save\nwhat was left of the France he\nloved, but he sacrificed the kind\nof Frenchmen he despised.\nFALSE TEETH\nRock, Slide or Slip?\nFASTEETH, an Improved powder to\nbe sprinkled on upper or lower plates,\nholds false teeth more flrmly In place.\nDo not slide, slip or rock. No gummy,\njtooey, pasty taste or feeling. FAS\nTEETH Is alkaline (non-acid). Does not\n\u2022our. Checks \"plate odor\" (denture\nbreath). Get FASTEETH at any drug\n\u2022tore.\nYou can\u2019t cuss Franco in print.\nThe typewriter\u2019s \u201co\u201d and \"e\" are\nequally dirty circles, and the lino\ntyper always thinks you mean\nFrance.\nDorothy Thompson says she ha*\nspent a journalistic lifetime fight\ning for \u201ca world organized under\nlaw.\u201d Sorry, we didn\u2019t hear you\nthe other 30 years.\n.V I\nI\n1 I\nj\nGARDNER\u2019S VELVET\nICE SHERBET\ni DELICIOUS DELIGHTFUL\ni TO SERVE!\n\nI\nStop by on your way home for a container of our ice\ni\ncream or fruit sherbet. A simple, effortless dessert every- j\nI one loves; and it fits right in with menu planning for\ngood nutrition. Several f